msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:1
msgid "2. The manifest"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:3
msgid ""
"Everything `haw` does starts from one file: `haw.toml`, the **manifest**. "
"It's your _intent_ — which repos exist, where they live, which revision you "
"want, and how they compose into stacks. In this chapter you'll write a real "
"one, top to bottom, and build the mental model. We won't sync yet — that's "
"the next chapter. Here we get the _declaration_ right first."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:11
msgid ""
"_A stack is just building blocks — repos snapped together under one name, "
"declared in the manifest._"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:17
msgid "Declare a <strong>remote</strong> once and reuse it across repos."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:18
msgid ""
"Add <strong>repos</strong>, each with a <code>rev</code> (branch, tag, or "
"SHA) and free-form <code>groups</code>."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:19
msgid "Compose repos into named <strong>stacks</strong> — shared, never copied."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:20
msgid ""
"Reach for <strong>overlays</strong> when one repo needs per-variant "
"overrides."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:21
msgid "Read a whole <code>haw.toml</code> and know exactly what it will do."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:25
msgid "🛠️ 1. Create a workspace"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:27
msgid ""
"Make an empty directory and drop in a manifest. We'll use small, real public "
"repos from GitHub's `octocat` account — the same ones the shipped "
"[`examples/quickstart`](https://github.com/Nastwinns/hawser/tree/main/examples/quickstart) "
"uses — so that next chapter you can actually `haw sync` this over HTTPS with "
"no authentication."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:37
msgid "Now create `haw.toml` with this content:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:39
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[remote.gh]\n"
"url = \"https://github.com/octocat\"\n"
"forge = \"github\"\n"
"\n"
"[repo.hello-world]\n"
"remote = \"gh\"\n"
"repo = \"Hello-World.git\"\n"
"rev = \"master\"\n"
"groups = [\"core\"]\n"
"\n"
"[repo.spoon-knife]\n"
"remote = \"gh\"\n"
"repo = \"Spoon-Knife.git\"\n"
"rev = \"main\"\n"
"groups = [\"web\"]\n"
"\n"
"# `site` composes the two repos into one named stack.\n"
"[stack.site]\n"
"repos = [\"hello-world\", \"spoon-knife\"]\n"
"description = \"A shared core repo plus the fork-demo front end.\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:62
msgid ""
"Read that top to bottom, because it _is_ the mental model. Let's take it one "
"block at a time."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:65
msgid "🌐 2. The remote — name a base URL once"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:67
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[remote.gh]\n"
"url = \"https://github.com/octocat\"\n"
"forge = \"github\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:73
msgid ""
"A `[remote.NAME]` names a base URL once so you don't repeat it on every "
"repo. `forge` tells `haw` which API to speak later (for PRs, CI, and so on) "
"— `github`, `gitlab`, or `bitbucket`. You can declare several remotes; a "
"fleet can span forges, and later a changeset can open a PR on one and an MR "
"on another from a single command."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:78
msgid "📦 3. The repos — one declaration each"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:80
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[repo.hello-world]\n"
"remote = \"gh\"\n"
"repo = \"Hello-World.git\"\n"
"rev = \"master\"\n"
"groups = [\"core\"]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:88
msgid "Each `[repo.NAME]` declares one repository:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:90
msgid ""
"`remote` + `repo` — which remote it lives on and its path there. Combined, "
"they resolve to `https://github.com/octocat/Hello-World.git`."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:92
msgid ""
"`rev` — **the revision you want**: a branch (`master`), a tag (`v6.1.2`), or "
"an exact SHA. `haw` auto-detects which kind it is. This is your _intent_ — a "
"moving branch until the lockfile freezes it (next chapter)."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:95
msgid ""
"`groups` — free-form labels you'll filter commands by later (e.g. `haw "
"status --group core`). A repo can be in several groups."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:100
msgid ""
"**`rev` is intent, not a pin.** Writing `rev = \"master\"` means \"track "
"master.\" Nothing is frozen until you sync and a **lockfile** records the "
"exact commit — that's the whole reproducibility story, and it's the entire "
"point of Chapter 3."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:106
msgid "🧱 4. Stacks — compose repos under a name"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:108
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[stack.site]\n"
"repos = [\"hello-world\", \"spoon-knife\"]\n"
"description = \"A shared core repo plus the fork-demo front end.\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:114
msgid ""
"A **stack** is a named composition of repos. It doesn't copy anything — it "
"just says \"these repos, together, under this name.\" One manifest can "
"define several stacks that _share_ the same repos:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:118
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[stack.site]\n"
"repos = [\"hello-world\", \"spoon-knife\"]\n"
"\n"
"[stack.core-only]\n"
"repos = [\"hello-world\"]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:126
msgid ""
"`hello-world` appears in both stacks, but there's only ever one clone of it "
"on disk. Stacks are how you carve a big fleet into the working sets you "
"actually build and test together — you'll `haw switch <stack>` between them, "
"and scope commands to one with `--stack`."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:131
msgid "🧬 5. Overlays — per-variant overrides (when you need them)"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:133
msgid ""
"Most repos need nothing more than the fields above. But sometimes _one_ repo "
"should look slightly different in a particular composition — a different "
"branch for a release variant, say. That's an **overlay**: a named set of "
"per-repo overrides applied at lock time."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:137
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[repo.app-mqtt]\n"
"remote = \"gh\"\n"
"repo = \"app-mqtt.git\"\n"
"rev = \"main\"\n"
"\n"
"# Override app-mqtt's rev only when the `release` overlay is active.\n"
"[overlay.release.app-mqtt]\n"
"rev = \"release/2.x\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:148
msgid ""
"With the `release` overlay active, `app-mqtt` locks to `release/2.x` instead "
"of `main`; everything else stays put. Reach for overlays only when a repo "
"genuinely needs to vary by variant — for the rest of this course we won't "
"need one. See [CLI design](../CLI-DESIGN.md) for the full overlay semantics."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:155
msgid ""
"**Tip:** You don't have to hand-write every repo. `haw repo add` and `haw "
"stack add` edit the manifest for you, and `haw import` converts an existing "
"`west.yml` or Google-`repo` `default.xml` straight into a `haw.toml`."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:161
msgid "🗺️ 6. The whole picture"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:163
msgid "Here's the manifest as a shape — intent flowing down into stacks:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:174
msgid ""
"That's the complete mental model of the manifest: **remotes** name where, "
"**repos** declare what and which `rev`, **groups** slice them, **stacks** "
"compose them, and **overlays** tweak them per variant. Nothing here has "
"touched the network or the disk yet — it's pure declaration."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:181
msgid ""
"**You just declared a fleet.** A remote, two repos, and a stack — that's a "
"real, syncable `haw.toml`. It scales the same way to a hundred repos and a "
"dozen stacks."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:190
msgid "Make the manifest your own — no sync required, this is all declaration:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:192
msgid ""
"Add a third repo to <code>haw.toml</code> — try "
"<code>octocat/git-consortium.git</code> on the <code>gh</code> remote — give "
"it a <code>rev</code> and put it in a new group."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:193
msgid ""
"Add it to the <code>site</code> stack's <code>repos</code> list, then add a "
"second stack, <code>core-only</code>, that lists just "
"<code>hello-world</code>. Notice the repo is <em>shared</em>, not copied."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:194
msgid ""
"Sketch on paper what you expect on disk after a sync: how many clones? "
"(Hint: one per <em>repo</em>, no matter how many stacks reference it.)"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:200
msgid ""
"The **manifest** (`haw.toml`) is your _intent_ — nothing is cloned or frozen "
"until you sync."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:202
msgid "`[remote.NAME]` names a base URL + forge once; repos reference it."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:203
msgid ""
"`[repo.NAME]` declares one repo with a `rev` (branch/tag/SHA, auto-detected) "
"and free-form `groups`."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:205
msgid ""
"`[stack.NAME]` composes repos under a name — **shared, never copied**; a "
"repo can be in many stacks and groups."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:207
msgid ""
"`[overlay.…]` applies per-variant overrides at lock time, for the rare repo "
"that must vary."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/02-the-manifest.md:212
msgid ""
"You've declared the fleet. Now let's make it real — clone it, freeze it to a "
"lockfile, and watch `haw` catch drift → [3. Sync and the "
"lockfile](03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md)."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:1
msgid "3. Sync and the lockfile"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:3
msgid ""
"This is where it clicks. You have a `haw.toml` from the last chapter. Now "
"you'll run `haw sync` to clone the fleet for real, read the lockfile that "
"freezes it to exact commits, prove it's reproducible, and — deliberately — "
"break something to watch `haw` catch drift."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:7
msgid ""
"Everything here clones over HTTPS with no authentication, so you can "
"actually run every command as you read. Keep the `my-first-stack` workspace "
"from Chapter 2 open."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:12
msgid ""
"_Sync clones the fleet; the lockfile freezes it to exact commits — the whole "
"reproducibility trick._"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:18
msgid ""
"Run <code>haw sync</code> to clone the fleet and generate "
"<code>haw.lock</code>."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:19
msgid ""
"Read the fleet with <code>haw tree</code> and <code>haw status</code>, and "
"understand every column."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:20
msgid ""
"Read the lockfile's real fields — <code>rev</code> (the resolved SHA), "
"<code>source-rev</code>, and <code>branch</code>."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:21
msgid ""
"Re-sync and confirm it's idempotent — the lock, not the branch, is now the "
"truth."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:22
msgid ""
"Cause <strong>drift</strong> on purpose and catch it with <code>haw "
"verify</code> (exit 3), then restore."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:26
msgid ""
"![Composing a stack: sync, tree, status, and the "
"lockfile](../assets/cli-compose.gif)"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:28
msgid ""
"_The full compose loop you're about to run: `sync` clones the fleet, then "
"`tree` / `status` read it and the lock pins it._"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:30
msgid "🔄 1. Sync — clone everything and write the lock"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:32
msgid "One command materializes the tree:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:38
msgid ""
"`haw` resolves each repo's `rev` to an exact commit, clones it, and — "
"because there's no lockfile yet — writes one. You'll see progress per repo "
"and a summary. Afterwards, look around:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:47
msgid ""
"There they are: two **real, complete Git clones**, plus a brand-new "
"`haw.lock`. No submodules, no symlinks — you could `cd hello-world && git "
"log` and it's just Git."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:52
msgid ""
"**Tip:** `haw sync` is _idempotent_. Run it again and, since the lock "
"already pins exact SHAs, `haw` just makes sure your tree matches — no "
"surprises, safe to repeat in scripts and CI."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:58
msgid "🔍 2. Explore the fleet"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:60
msgid "Now the read commands. First, the shape of things:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:66
msgid ""
"```console\n"
"haw.toml\n"
"└─ site\n"
"   ├─ hello-world  master  (https://github.com/octocat/Hello-World.git)\n"
"   └─ spoon-knife  main  (https://github.com/octocat/Spoon-Knife.git)\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:73
msgid ""
"That's your stack → repo tree: the stack `site`, the two repos under it, "
"each with its declared rev and origin."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:76
msgid "Now the health check:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:88
msgid ""
"Read the columns left to right: the repo, the branch it's on, its short HEAD "
"SHA, whether the working tree has uncommitted changes (**DIRTY**), and "
"whether HEAD differs from the locked SHA (**DRIFT**). Right now everything "
"is clean and in sync — the dashes mean \"all good.\""
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:95
msgid ""
"**Tip:** On a terminal these are color-coded — cyan repo names, yellow revs, "
"green for clean, red for drift. Pipe the output anywhere and it falls back "
"to plain text automatically (it honors `NO_COLOR`), so it's script-friendly "
"by default."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:101
msgid "🔒 3. Read the lockfile"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:103
msgid ""
"Open `haw.lock` in your editor. Each repo is pinned to a **full 40-character "
"SHA** in its `rev` field — the exact commit, not the branch name — while "
"`source-rev` records what you _asked_ for and `branch` records the branch "
"that SHA came from:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:107
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"# excerpt — your SHAs will differ\n"
"[[repo]]\n"
"name = \"hello-world\"\n"
"url = \"https://github.com/octocat/Hello-World.git\"\n"
"path = \"hello-world\"\n"
"rev = \"7fd1a60b01f91b314f59955a4e4d4e80d8edf11d\"   # the resolved commit — "
"this is the pin\n"
"source-rev = \"master\"                               # what you declared in "
"haw.toml\n"
"branch = \"master\"                                   # the branch that SHA "
"was resolved from\n"
"groups = [\"core\"]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:119
msgid ""
"This is the whole reproducibility trick. Your manifest said \"master\" (a "
"moving target), but the lock froze the _exact_ commit master pointed at when "
"you synced — that's the SHA now in `rev`. `source-rev` remembers your intent "
"(`master`) and `branch` remembers where it came from, so `haw` can later "
"re-resolve if you ask. Commit `haw.lock` alongside `haw.toml`, and anyone "
"who clones and runs `haw sync` gets **precisely these commits** — not "
"whatever `master` happens to be today."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:128
msgid ""
"**Don't hand-edit it.** `haw.lock` is generated. You commit it, but you "
"change intent in `haw.toml` and let `haw lock` / `haw sync` regenerate the "
"lock."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:133
msgid "♻️ 4. Prove it's reproducible — re-run sync"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:139
msgid ""
"Because the lock exists, `haw` syncs _to the pinned SHAs_, not to wherever "
"the branches have moved. Run `haw status` again and you'll see the same "
"clean fleet. That idempotence is the point: the lock, not the branch, is the "
"source of truth now."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:143
msgid "🧭 5. See drift with your own eyes"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:145
msgid ""
"Reproducibility is only useful if you can _detect_ when the tree wanders off "
"the baseline. Let's cause that on purpose. Move one repo to a different "
"commit by hand:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:150
msgid "# step one commit back — now HEAD ≠ the locked SHA\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:154
msgid "Ask `haw` what it thinks:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:166
msgid ""
"There it is — **DRIFT: YES** on `hello-world`. Checking out a specific "
"commit also detaches HEAD (hence `(detached)` in the BRANCH column), and its "
"HEAD no longer matches the locked SHA. `haw status` flagged it, but for CI "
"you want a command that _fails_ on drift. That's `verify`:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:176
msgid ""
"`verify` asserts the on-disk tree matches `haw.lock` and **exits 3** when it "
"doesn't — a clean, scriptable drift gate. Check the exit code:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:180
#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:201
#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:173
msgid "\"exit code: $?\""
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:189
msgid ""
"That exit `3` is what a CI pipeline keys on: \"the tree drifted from the "
"lock — stop the build.\" (When everything matches, `verify` prints "
"`verified: tree matches haw.lock (2 repos)` and exits `0`.)"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:195
msgid "_`haw verify` finding drift in CI right before release._"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:197
msgid "Now put it back. `haw sync` restores every repo to its locked SHA:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:209
msgid ""
"Clean again. You just watched the full loop: **declare → sync → pin → detect "
"drift → restore.**"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:214
msgid ""
"**You just did the core loop.** Declare intent, pin it, detect drift, and "
"restore the baseline — the same four moves scale from two octocat repos to a "
"hundred-repo fleet."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:223
msgid "Prove the lockfile really is the source of truth:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:225
msgid ""
"Open <code>haw.lock</code> and find each repo's pinned SHA in its "
"<code>rev</code> field. Confirm it's a 40-char commit, not a branch name, "
"and that <code>source-rev</code> still shows what you declared."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:226
msgid ""
"Drift one repo on purpose (<code>cd hello-world && git checkout HEAD~1 && cd "
"..</code>), run <code>haw verify; echo $?</code>, and confirm you get exit "
"code <code>3</code>."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:227
msgid ""
"Run <code>haw sync</code> to restore, then <code>haw verify; echo $?</code> "
"again — back to exit <code>0</code>. That round trip is the reproducibility "
"guarantee."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:233
msgid ""
"`haw sync` clones every repo and writes `haw.lock` — real Git clones, no "
"submodules/symlinks. It's idempotent."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:235
msgid ""
"`haw tree` shows the stack→repo shape; `haw status` shows "
"branch/HEAD/**dirty**/**drift** per repo."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:237
msgid ""
"`haw.lock` pins each repo to an exact 40-char SHA in `rev`, with "
"`source-rev` (your declared intent) and `branch` alongside — commit it for "
"byte-identical rebuilds."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/03-sync-and-the-lockfile.md:239
msgid ""
"**Drift** = HEAD differs from the lock. `haw status` flags it; `haw verify` "
"**exits 3** on drift (your CI gate). `haw sync` restores the baseline."
msgstr ""

