#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:140
msgid "`c`"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:140
msgid "**checkout** the PR branch locally"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:142
msgid ""
"Every write is **confirm-gated** with a `y/n` so you never merge by "
"fat-finger. `o` opens the cursor row in your browser. So the full "
"cross-forge flow from Chapter 5 — see PRs, approve, merge — is right here, "
"keyboard-only, all under `a`."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:146
msgid "📂 6. Browsing files & branches — any ref, local or forge"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:148
msgid ""
"Press **`f`** on any repo to open its **file browser** — a _read-only_ view "
"(it never stages or commits, only reads). Three keys turn it into a proper "
"code explorer:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:153 ./CLI-DESIGN.md:175 ./CLI-DESIGN.md:189
msgid "`T`"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:153
msgid ""
"**toggle** the flat one-directory list ⇄ a navigable **tree** (`▸`/`▾` to "
"expand/collapse, `→`/`Enter` expand, `←` collapse)"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:154
msgid ""
"**ref picker** — pick a branch or tag from the list, or type any SHA; the "
"view reloads _as of_ that ref and the header shows `@ <ref>`"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:155 ./CLI-DESIGN.md:177
msgid "`e`"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:155
msgid "**edit** the file under the cursor in your `$EDITOR` (local files only)"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:156 ./CLI-DESIGN.md:178 ./CLI-DESIGN.md:190
msgid "`R`"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:156
msgid "**toggle** local disk ⇄ the forge"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:158
msgid ""
"The payoff: with `r` you can read a file **as it exists on any branch of the "
"remote** — across GitHub, GitLab, or Bitbucket — **without checking anything "
"out**. Point at a colleague's `feature/x` branch, read the file straight "
"from the forge API, and never touch your working tree. `e` is the one "
"exception to read-only: it hands the file to your editor for a quick local "
"fix, then reloads the listing."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:164
msgid "💬 7. The command bar — one language for CLI and TUI"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:166
msgid ""
"Press **`:`** to open the command bar (the command palette). Its verbs "
"_mirror the CLI you already learned_, and the status line echoes the exact "
"command each one runs — so the cockpit doubles as a way to discover the CLI:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:178
msgid "Learn one, know both. `:name` also jumps the cursor to a repo by name."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:180
msgid "🎨 8. Two more views, and themes"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:182
msgid ""
"**`7`** (`:plugins`) — the **Plugins** view: every available plugin "
"(manifest `[plugins]` keys unioned with `haw-*` executables on your `PATH`); "
"`Enter` runs one and shows its output in a panel. You'll build one that "
"lands here in [Chapter 8](08-build-a-plugin-mcp.md)."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:186
msgid ""
"**`:errors`** (`:err`) — the **Errors** view: a rolling log of this "
"session's failures, so a transient error never scrolls away before you can "
"read it."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:189
msgid ""
"**Themes.** Six built-in skins — `catppuccin` (default), `dracula`, `nord`, "
"`gruvbox`, `solarized`, `monochrome`. Switch live with `:theme nord`, set "
"one at startup with `HAW_THEME=nord haw`, and `NO_COLOR` forces `monochrome`."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:193
msgid ""
"Press **`?`** any time for the help overlay, and `q` (or `Ctrl-C`) to quit."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:197
msgid ""
"**Tip:** Every heavy action runs on a background worker, so the UI never "
"freezes while a sync, a fetch, or a forge call is in flight. Keep navigating."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:206
msgid ""
"No workspace or network needed — the demo controller has everything to poke "
"at:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:208
msgid ""
"Launch <code>haw dash --demo</code>. Move with "
"<code>↑</code>/<code>↓</code>, then press <code>Enter</code> to drill into a "
"repo and <code>Esc</code> to come back — feel the read → drill → act → back "
"rhythm."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:209
msgid ""
"Press <code>Space</code> to mark a couple of repos (watch the "
"<code>◉</code>), then <code>/</code> to fuzzy-filter the grid. Press "
"<code>3</code> for PRs and <code>4</code> for CI, then <code>a</code> to see "
"the actions menu. Press <code>?</code> for the help overlay."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:210
msgid ""
"Press <code>f</code> on a repo to browse its files, then <code>T</code> for "
"the tree and <code>r</code> to read a file as of another branch or tag. "
"Press <code>b</code> to come back."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:211
msgid ""
"Press <code>:</code> and type <code>:theme nord</code>. The skin changes "
"live — and the status line echoes the exact command, so the cockpit is "
"teaching you the CLI as you go."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:217
msgid ""
"Bare `haw` (or `haw dash --demo`) opens the cockpit — a live `haw status` "
"you can act on."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:218
msgid "The loop is **read → drill (`Enter`) → act → back (`Esc`)**."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:219
msgid ""
"Fleet keys: `s` sync, `f` files, `x` shell, `!` exec, `/` filter, `p` "
"problems, `Space` mark, `r` run, `g` goto, `a` actions."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:221
msgid ""
"View jumps are the digits **`1`–`7`**: `1` fleet, `2` changesets, `3` PRs, "
"`4` CI, `5` tree, `6` governance, `7` plugins. In PRs/CI, `a` (actions) does "
"merge/approve/checkout (confirm-gated), `d` diff, `l` logs, `f` PR files."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:224
msgid ""
"File browser (`f`): `T` toggles tree, `r` picks a branch/tag/SHA (read any "
"ref, local or forge, no checkout), `e` edits locally, `R` toggles local ⇄ "
"forge."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:226
msgid ""
"`:` is a command bar (palette) mirroring the CLI; `:plugins` and `:errors` "
"reach those views; six themes via `:theme` / `HAW_THEME`."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/04-the-tui-cockpit.md:231
msgid ""
"You've seen the whole cockpit read the fleet. Now the signature move it "
"drives — shipping _one feature across many repos_ as a single coordinated "
"changeset → [5. Changesets across repos](05-changesets-across-repos.md)."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:1
msgid "5. Changesets across repos"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:3
msgid ""
"This is hawser's signature feature — the one that pays for the whole tool. "
"In this chapter you'll take _one_ feature that touches _several_ repos and "
"drive it as a single unit: one branch across all of them, cross-linked pull "
"requests, and a merge that lands in the right order."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:10
msgid ""
"_One feature, one review flow — even when the code is spread across repos "
"and forges._"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:16
msgid ""
"Understand what a <strong>changeset</strong> is: one feature = one branch "
"across N repos."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:17
msgid ""
"Start a changeset with <code>haw change start</code> — the same branch in "
"every repo, in one move."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:18
msgid ""
"Track the whole feature on one screen with <code>haw change status</code>."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:19
msgid ""
"Open cross-linked PR/MRs with <code>haw change request</code> — across "
"GitHub, GitLab, and Bitbucket."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:20
msgid ""
"Merge in dependency order with <code>haw change land</code>, so "
"<code>main</code> never breaks."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:24
msgid ""
"![Driving a cross-repo changeset from the CLI](../assets/cli-changeset.gif)"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:26
msgid ""
"_One feature, many repos: `change start` branches them all, `status` "
"aggregates, `request` opens linked PRs._"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:28
msgid "😤 1. The pain this removes"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:30
msgid "Think back to the last time a feature spanned repos. You did this dance:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:32
msgid "`git checkout -b feature` in repo A. And repo B. And repo C."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:33
msgid "Push each. Open a PR in A. Then B. Then C."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:34
msgid "Chase reviews across three separate PR pages."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:35
msgid ""
"Merge them — and remember that the shared library **must** merge _before_ "
"the services that depend on it, or `main` breaks."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:38
msgid ""
"Nothing tied those three PRs together. There was no single artifact that "
"said \"these are one feature.\" A **changeset** is exactly that artifact: "
"one feature = one branch across N repos, with linked PR/MRs and an ordered "
"land."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:44
msgid ""
"Changesets need a real forge (GitHub, GitLab, or Bitbucket) and a token to "
"open PRs. The `start` and `status` steps are local and safe to try anywhere; "
"`request` and `land` talk to the forge. We'll flag which is which."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:50
msgid "🌱 2. Start the changeset"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:52
msgid "You name the feature and (optionally) the repos it touches:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:65
msgid ""
"In one move, `haw` created the **same branch** — `change/FEAT-42` by default "
"— in each of the three repos. Now you make your changes and commit in each "
"repo as normal Git. The branch name ties them together."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:69
msgid "A few useful options at start time:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:71
msgid ""
"`--repos a,b,c` — limit to the repos the feature touches (default: all "
"repos)."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:72
msgid "`--branch <name>` — use a custom branch name instead of `change/<id>`."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:73
msgid ""
"`--skip-branch` — adopt whatever branch each repo is already on, instead of "
"creating one."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:74
msgid ""
"`--label <l>` — attach a label (repeatable) that gets forwarded to the "
"PR/MRs later."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:76
msgid "📊 3. Watch it come together — `change status`"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:78
msgid "At any point, get the whole feature on one screen:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:84
msgid ""
"This aggregates, per repo: the branch, whether each repo is **on it**, "
"whether it's dirty, its HEAD — and once PRs exist, the review state and CI "
"status of each PR/MR. Before any PRs are open it looks like this (run "
"against the `DEMO-1` changeset from the \"Your turn\" below, so the repos "
"are the two octocat clones):"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:97
msgid ""
"Instead of three browser tabs, one dashboard. It's the changeset equivalent "
"of `haw status`."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:102
msgid ""
"**Tip:** Add `--format json` to `change status` (it emits a stable "
"`haw.change-status/1` document) when you want to pipe the state into another "
"tool or a script:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:105
msgid ""
"```console\n"
"$ haw change status DEMO-1 --format json\n"
"{\n"
"  \"id\": \"DEMO-1\",\n"
"  \"repos\": [\n"
"    {\n"
"      \"branch\": \"change/DEMO-1\",\n"
"      \"dirty\": false,\n"
"      \"head\": \"7fd1a60b01f91b314f59955a4e4d4e80d8edf11d\",\n"
"      \"missing\": false,\n"
"      \"name\": \"hello-world\",\n"
"      \"on_branch\": true,\n"
"      \"pr\": null\n"
"    }\n"
"  ],\n"
"  \"schema\": \"haw.change-status/1\"\n"
"}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:126
msgid "🔀 4. Open the pull requests — `change request`"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:128
msgid ""
"When your branches are pushed and ready, one command opens **cross-linked "
"PR/MRs** — one per repo — on whichever forge each repo lives on:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:135
msgid ""
"Here's the quietly powerful part: your repos don't all have to be on the "
"same forge. `haw` speaks **GitHub, GitLab, _and_ Bitbucket**, so a feature "
"spanning a GitHub service and a GitLab library gets a PR on GitHub _and_ an "
"MR on GitLab, cross-linked, from this one command. Any labels you passed at "
"`start` are forwarded here. Target a specific base branch with `--base "
"<branch>`."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:143
msgid ""
"This step needs a forge token in your environment — e.g. `export "
"GITHUB_TOKEN=$(gh auth token)`. `haw` reads tokens from env vars only, never "
"stores them. Read-only steps (`start`, `status`) need no token."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:149
msgid "🛬 5. Land in dependency order — `change land`"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:151
msgid ""
"Reviews are in, checks are green. Now merge — but in the _right order_. "
"Remember `proto` is a shared library that `api` and `billing` depend on. "
"Merging a service before its library lands is how you break `main`."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:155
msgid ""
"`haw` knows the order because your manifest declares it. Recall the `deps` "
"key from the microservices example:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:158
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[repo.gateway]\n"
"deps = [\"proto\"]     # proto must land before gateway\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:163
msgid ""
"So `land` merges the PR/MRs in **stable topological order** — dependencies "
"first — and stops at the first failure rather than leaving a half-merged "
"mess:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:180
msgid ""
"**Forge step — needs a token.** Like `request`, `land` talks to the forge "
"and requires a token (e.g. `export GITHUB_TOKEN=$(gh auth token)`) plus "
"merge rights on each repo. The output above is illustrative: against the "
"public read-only `octocat` repos this course uses, `request`/`land` can't "
"push or merge, so don't expect these lines without your own writable repos "
"and a token."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:188
msgid ""
"`proto` merged first because everything depends on it; the services "
"followed. One command, correct order, no broken `main`."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:193
msgid "_One command. Five repos merged in the right order. We did it._"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:195
msgid ""
"![The low-level `haw merge` flow — plan, resolve conflicts, then clean "
"up](../assets/cli-merge.gif)"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:197
msgid ""
"_`change land` merges the linked PR/MRs in topological order — dependencies "
"first — and stops at the first failure._"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:199
msgid "🖼️ 6. The value, in one picture"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:212
msgid ""
"You never lost track of which PRs were \"the feature,\" you never merged in "
"the wrong order, and you drove all of it from four commands. That's the "
"whole point of a changeset: **a multi-repo feature that behaves like a "
"single, coherent change.**"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:218
msgid ""
"**Tip:** Working across repos and want to hop into one? `haw change goto "
"FEAT-42 <repo>` prints its path so you can `cd \"$(haw change goto FEAT-42 "
"api)\"`. And `haw change snapshot save <name>` records every repo's branch + "
"HEAD so you can restore the exact multi-repo state later."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:229
msgid ""
"The local half of the flow needs no forge token, so try it in a workspace "
"right now:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:231
msgid ""
"Run <code>haw change start DEMO-1 --repos hello-world,spoon-knife</code> and "
"confirm the same <code>change/DEMO-1</code> branch appears in both repos "
"(peek with <code>haw run 'git branch --show-current'</code>)."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:232
msgid ""
"Run <code>haw change status DEMO-1</code> and read the aggregated "
"branch/dirty/HEAD — one dashboard instead of two tabs."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:233
msgid ""
"Now sketch it on paper: for a real feature spanning a shared lib and two "
"services, in what order must they <code>land</code>? (Lib first — that's the "
"<code>deps</code> key doing its job.)"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:239
msgid ""
"A **changeset** is one feature across N repos: a shared branch, linked "
"PR/MRs, an ordered merge."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:241
msgid ""
"`haw change start <id> --repos a,b,c` creates the same branch in each repo."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:242
msgid ""
"`haw change status <id>` aggregates branch + review + CI across the whole "
"feature."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:243
msgid ""
"`haw change request <id>` opens cross-linked PR/MRs on **GitHub, GitLab, and "
"Bitbucket**."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:244
msgid ""
"`haw change land <id>` merges in **dependency order** (from each repo's "
"`deps`), stopping on the first failure."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:246
msgid ""
"`start`/`status` are local; `request`/`land` need a forge token in the "
"environment."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/05-changesets-across-repos.md:250
msgid ""
"You can ship a feature across the fleet. Now let's _build, test, and verify_ "
"the whole thing — the daily workflow that keeps it green → [6. Build, test, "
"and verify](06-build-test-and-verify.md)."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:1
msgid "6. Build, test, and verify"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:3
msgid ""
"You can compose a fleet, pin it, and ship changesets across it. Now let's "
"make it _earn its keep_ day to day. The promise of a multi-repo tool is "
"simple: do something across every repo at once, in parallel, without a "
"hand-rolled `for` loop — and then gate the whole fleet so CI stays green."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:8
msgid ""
"In this chapter you'll run arbitrary commands across the fleet, wire up "
"`build` and `test`, search every repo in one shot, and use `verify` as the "
"drift gate that ties it together. Keep the `my-first-stack` workspace open."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:14
msgid ""
"_One command in, the whole fleet processed in parallel — no hand-rolled "
"`for` loop._"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:20
msgid "Fan any command across every repo with <code>haw run</code>."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:21
msgid ""
"Declare <code>build =</code> / <code>test =</code> per repo and drive the "
"whole fleet with <code>haw build</code> / <code>haw test</code> — "
"live-streamed, per-repo color."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:22
msgid "Search every repo at once with <code>haw grep</code>."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:23
msgid ""
"Gate the fleet against the lock with <code>haw verify</code> — the CI drift "
"gate."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:24
msgid ""
"Control the blast radius with <code>\\-j</code> (parallelism) and "
"<code>\\--group</code> (scope)."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:28
msgid ""
"![Running commands and verifying across the "
"fleet](../assets/cli-run-verify.gif)"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:30
msgid ""
"_`haw run` fans a command across every repo in parallel; `verify` gates the "
"fleet against the lock._"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:32
msgid "⚙️ 1. Run any command across every repo — `haw run`"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:34
msgid ""
"The workhorse. `haw run` takes a command _positionally_ and runs it in every "
"repo, in parallel:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:38
msgid "'git log -1 --oneline'"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:49
msgid ""
"`haw` groups the output per repo so you always know which repo said what. "
"Anything you'd type in one repo works: `git fetch`, `git status -s`, a "
"linter, a shell one-liner."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:54
msgid ""
"**Tip:** Quote the command. `haw run 'git status -s'` passes the whole "
"string as one command; without quotes your shell would try to interpret the "
"flags itself."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:59
msgid "🔨 2. Declare build and test — then run them fleet-wide"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:61
msgid ""
"`haw` stays build-system-agnostic: each repo names the shell command that "
"builds or tests _it_, and `haw` fans those out. You declare them in the "
"manifest with `build =` and `test =`."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:65
msgid ""
"In the real world each repo brings its _own_ toolchain. Here's the shape, "
"from the shipped "
"[`microservices`](https://github.com/Nastwinns/hawser/tree/main/examples/microservices) "
"example:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:69
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[repo.proto]\n"
"build = \"buf generate\"\n"
"test  = \"buf lint\"\n"
"\n"
"[repo.gateway]\n"
"build = \"go build ./...\"\n"
"test  = \"go test ./...\"\n"
"\n"
"[repo.billing]\n"
"build = \"cargo build --release\"\n"
"test  = \"cargo test\"\n"
"\n"
"[repo.accounts]\n"
"build = \"npm ci && npm run build\"\n"
"test  = \"npm test\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:87
msgid ""
"Our octocat repos have nothing real to compile — and if you run `haw build` "
"now, it tells you so and exits non-zero:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:95
msgid ""
"So let's declare trivial commands to see the mechanism. Add a `build =` and "
"`test =` line to **both** repos in your `my-first-stack/haw.toml`:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:98
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[repo.hello-world]\n"
"remote = \"gh\"\n"
"repo = \"Hello-World.git\"\n"
"rev = \"master\"\n"
"groups = [\"core\"]\n"
"build = \"echo built\"\n"
"test  = \"echo tested\"\n"
"\n"
"[repo.spoon-knife]\n"
"remote = \"gh\"\n"
"repo = \"Spoon-Knife.git\"\n"
"rev = \"main\"\n"
"groups = [\"web\"]\n"
"build = \"echo built\"\n"
"test  = \"echo tested\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:116
msgid "Now two commands drive the whole fleet:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:119
msgid "# runs every repo's `build =`, in parallel\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:120
msgid "# runs every repo's `test =`, in parallel\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:132
msgid ""
"Output is **live-streamed** as each repo runs and grouped under a per-repo "
"header, so on a color terminal each repo's stream carries its own color — "
"you can read a fleet-wide build without losing track of which repo produced "
"which line. Repos that don't declare the command (or aren't cloned) are "
"simply skipped. And here's the detail that makes this a CI building block:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:140
msgid ""
"**CI building block:** `haw build` and `haw test` **exit non-zero if any "
"repo fails**. That's why the same command you run locally drops straight "
"into a pipeline — the pipeline stops when any repo's build breaks."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:146
msgid "🔎 3. Search the whole fleet — `haw grep`"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:148
msgid ""
"Need to find every use of a symbol, a TODO, a deprecated API across _all_ "
"repos? `haw grep` fans `git grep` across every cloned repo at once:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:155
msgid ""
"```console\n"
"spoon-knife (1 hit(s))\n"
"  README.md:9:For some more information on how to fork a repository, [check "
"out our guide, \"Forking "
"Projects\"\"](http://guides.github.com/overviews/forking/). Thanks! "
":sparkling_heart:\n"
"1 hit(s) in 2 repo(s) for `guide`\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:161
msgid ""
"Each repo with a match gets a header and its hits underneath, and a final "
"line totals the hits and repos searched — a repo with no match just doesn't "
"appear. It searches tracked files via Git, so it's fast and ignores your "
"build artifacts for free. Scope it to one stack with `--stack <name>` when "
"the fleet is large."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:166
msgid "🛡️ 4. Verify — the CI gate"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:168
msgid ""
"Building and testing green is only half the story. Before any of it, CI must "
"prove the tree is _the one you pinned_ — no drift from `haw.lock`. That's "
"`haw verify`, which you met in Chapter 3:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:181
msgid ""
"`verify` asserts the on-disk tree matches the lock and **exits 3** on drift "
"— a clean, scriptable gate. It's the first real step of every pipeline: sync "
"to the lock, `verify` you're on it, _then_ build and test. Chapter 7 wires "
"the full `sync → verify → build → test` job."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:188
msgid ""
"**Tip:** `verify` reads the tree and the lock only — no network, no builds. "
"It's cheap enough to run as a git pre-commit hook (`haw hooks install`) so "
"drift never even reaches CI."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:194
msgid "🎚️ 5. Control the blast radius: parallelism and groups"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:196
msgid "Two levers keep fleet-wide commands under control."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:198
msgid ""
"**Parallelism — `-j`.** By default `haw` runs up to `min(cores, 8)` repos at "
"once. Cap it when a task is heavy (or a CI runner is small):"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:202
msgid "# at most 4 repos building/testing at a time\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:203
msgid "'git fetch'   # fully serial\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:206
msgid ""
"**Groups — `--group`.** Remember the `groups = [...]` labels from your "
"manifest? They exist precisely so you can act on a slice of the fleet. In "
"`my-first-stack`, `hello-world` is in group `core` and `spoon-knife` is in "
"`web`:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:219
msgid ""
"Only the `core` repo. The same `--group` filter works on `sync`, `status`, "
"and `run` (and `build`/`test`), and it's _repeatable_ — pass it twice to "
"select two groups. An empty filter means everything; a filter excludes "
"ungrouped repos."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/06-build-test-and-verify.md:224
msgid "'git log -1 --oneline'   # only core repos\n"
msgstr ""

