#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:26
msgid "🛡️ 1. First, the trust model — because it matters"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:28
msgid "Before you run `haw` on anything you didn't write, internalize one rule:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:32
msgid ""
"_Treat a `haw.toml` like a Makefile: powerful, and only run one you trust._"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:36
msgid ""
"**The manifest is trusted code.** A `haw.toml`'s `build`, `test`, `run`, and "
"`exec` commands are executed through _your_ shell."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:41
msgid ""
"Running `haw build`, `haw run`, or `haw sync` on an **untrusted** checkout "
"is equivalent to running its `Makefile`. Treat `haw.toml` exactly like a "
"`Makefile` or a `package.json` `scripts` block: **only run it on manifests "
"you trust.**"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:45
msgid "Two corollaries you already half-know:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:47
msgid ""
"**Plugins are trusted binaries.** `haw <name>` runs `haw-<name>` from your "
"`PATH` with your full environment (including any tokens). Install only "
"plugins you trust; keep `PATH` clean."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:50
msgid ""
"**Tokens live in the environment only.** `haw` reads forge tokens from env "
"vars at call time, and **never stores or logs them**. Git transport auth "
"stays with your existing SSH keys / credential helper — `haw` doesn't touch "
"it."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:54
msgid ""
"Read the full [trust model](../SECURITY.md) before you wire `haw` into "
"anything shared."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:56
msgid "🧩 2. Extend it with plugins — no fork required"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:58
msgid ""
"Before we wire the pipeline, meet the escape hatch that powers the "
"governance features below. `haw` follows the same pattern as `git`, `cargo`, "
"and `kubectl`: **any subcommand `haw` doesn't recognize is dispatched to a "
"`haw-<name>` executable on your `PATH`.**"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:64
msgid ""
"_A plugin is just a program that reads some JSON and prints some JSON — "
"write one in any language._"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:67
msgid "# not built in → runs `haw-jira sync`\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:70
msgid ""
"The plugin runs as a **separate process** (a broken plugin can never crash "
"`haw`), `haw` hands it the current fleet as JSON via `HAW_JSON` + stdin "
"(`haw.plugin/1`), and the plugin's exit code becomes `haw`'s — so a plugin "
"is a first-class CI gate. Discover, install, and scaffold them:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:76
msgid "# first-party + installed plugins\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:77
msgid "# the community index\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:78
msgid "# shells out to cargo install\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:79
msgid "# runnable skeleton (rust|python|go|shell)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:82
msgid ""
"The scaffold is a complete, runnable plugin: it reads the context, handles "
"`--help` and `--format json`, emits a `haw.plugin.report/1` document, and "
"fails open outside a workspace. Put it on `PATH` and it's instantly a `haw` "
"subcommand — no rebuild of `haw`."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:88
msgid ""
"**Tip:** `haw`'s own governance features — SBOM, signing, secret-gate — ship "
"_as plugins_ on exactly this model, so nothing here is second-class. The "
"full contract, JSON Schemas, and language bindings are in "
"[Plugins](../PLUGINS.md)."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/07-going-to-production.md:94
msgid ""
"The real power is **lifecycle hooks**: subscribe a plugin to a phase in "
"`[plugins]` and it fires automatically around fleet operations — which is "
"exactly how the supply-chain features below are wired."
msgstr ""

