#: ./learn/08-build-a-plugin-mcp.md:57
msgid "1. What a haw plugin actually is"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/08-build-a-plugin-mcp.md:59
msgid ""
"Let's start from zero. **A haw plugin is nothing more than an executable "
"program named `haw-<name>` that lives somewhere on your `PATH`.** That's the "
"whole idea. There is no plugin registry to sign up for, no dynamic library "
"to load, no special API to link against."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/08-build-a-plugin-mcp.md:63
msgid ""
"haw follows the same convention as `git`, `cargo`, and `kubectl`: when you "
"type a subcommand it doesn't recognize, it looks for a matching executable "
"and runs it. Here's the flow in words:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/08-build-a-plugin-mcp.md:67
msgid "You type `haw commit-ai`."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/08-build-a-plugin-mcp.md:68
msgid "haw checks its built-in subcommands. `commit-ai` isn't one of them."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/08-build-a-plugin-mcp.md:69
msgid ""
"haw searches every directory on your `PATH` for an executable named "
"`haw-commit-ai`."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/08-build-a-plugin-mcp.md:70
msgid ""
"It finds one, runs it as a **separate process**, and forwards your arguments "
"to it."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/08-build-a-plugin-mcp.md:71
msgid ""
"Whatever that program prints becomes the output; whatever exit code it "
"returns becomes haw's exit code."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/08-build-a-plugin-mcp.md:74
msgid ""
"So `haw commit-ai` is really just \"run the program `haw-commit-ai`, and "
"hand it some context about my workspace.\" This is called **PATH dispatch**, "
"and it's why you can ship `haw-jira`, `haw-sbom`, or `haw-whatever` without "
"ever touching haw's source code. A broken plugin can't crash haw, because it "
"runs in its own process."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/08-build-a-plugin-mcp.md:79
msgid "You can see exactly which directories haw scans:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/08-build-a-plugin-mcp.md:82
msgid "# prints the PATH directories haw searches for haw-* binaries\n"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/08-build-a-plugin-mcp.md:85
msgid ""
"We're going to build a plugin called **`haw-commit-ai`**. It has two faces, "
"both from a single script:"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/08-build-a-plugin-mcp.md:88
msgid ""
"As an ordinary plugin (`haw commit-ai`) it drafts commit messages and PR "
"text from your diffs."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/08-build-a-plugin-mcp.md:90
msgid ""
"As an **MCP server** it lets **Claude** read your workspace and diffs and "
"write the real commit and PR text itself — safely."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/08-build-a-plugin-mcp.md:93
msgid "We'll do the plain plugin first, then add the MCP face."
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/08-build-a-plugin-mcp.md:95
msgid "2. The context haw hands every plugin: `haw.plugin/1`"
msgstr ""

#: ./learn/08-build-a-plugin-mcp.md:97
msgid ""
"When haw runs your plugin, it doesn't just launch a blind program. It hands "
"the plugin a **context**: a JSON document that describes your workspace. "
"This document has a schema name, **`haw.plugin/1`**, and it is the contract "
"between haw and every plugin."
msgstr ""

