#: ./INTEGRATION.md:1
msgid "Integration recipes — wiring `haw` to your toolchain"
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:3
msgid ""
"`haw` never bundles or reimplements a compiler, a config generator, or an "
"emulator. It only **shells out** the per-repo `build =` / `test =` command "
"you declare (with the repo directory as the working directory, so `$PWD` "
"inside the command _is_ the repo path). That is the entire integration "
"surface: **put your toolchain's command in `build =`, and `haw` drives the "
"whole fleet** — in parallel, pinned to `haw.lock`, with a CI-grade exit code."
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:9
msgid ""
"So \"integrating haw\" is the same one move whether your compiler is `gcc`, "
"a Docker image, or a €50k licensed automotive suite. This page shows both:"
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:12
msgid ""
"**Recipes that were actually executed** (open toolchains: Docker "
"cross-compile, QEMU emulation, FreeRTOS) — with real captured output."
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:14
msgid ""
"**Wiring patterns** for proprietary/licensed tools (Vector, EB tresos, Green "
"Hills, IAR, Tasking, Renode) — the exact shape, honestly marked _not run "
"here_ (we don't have the licenses), so nothing is fabricated."
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:18
msgid ""
"**The one idea:** `haw build` / `haw test` run `build =` / `test =` per repo "
"and fail (non-zero) if any repo's command fails. Nothing in `haw` is ARM-, "
"Docker-, or QEMU-specific. Wrap any toolchain the same way."
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:24
msgid "Toolchain in a container (no host cross-toolchain needed)"
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:26
msgid ""
"You rarely install a cross-compiler on every developer's machine. Put it in "
"a Docker image once and reference it from `build =`. The two images used "
"below:"
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:53
msgid "Recipe 1 — Docker cross-compile (bare-metal ARM Cortex-M) ✅ _executed_"
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:55
msgid ""
"`littlefs` (a real fail-safe filesystem for MCUs) compiled to a "
"**Cortex-M4** static archive inside the toolchain image; the `test =` step "
"asserts the produced object is genuinely ARM."
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:59
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[repo.littlefs]\n"
"url    = \"https://github.com/littlefs-project/littlefs.git\"\n"
"rev    = \"master\"\n"
"groups = [\"firmware\"]\n"
"build  = \"docker run --rm -v \\\"$PWD\\\":/w -w /w haw-arm-gcc sh -c "
"'arm-none-eabi-gcc -mcpu=cortex-m4 -mthumb -Os -Wall -c lfs.c lfs_util.c && "
"arm-none-eabi-ar rcs lfs-cortexm4.a lfs.o lfs_util.o && arm-none-eabi-size "
"lfs-cortexm4.a'\"\n"
"test   = \"docker run --rm -v \\\"$PWD\\\":/w -w /w haw-arm-gcc sh -c "
"'arm-none-eabi-objdump -f lfs.o | grep -i \\\"architecture: arm\\\" && echo "
"CONFIRMED_ARM_CORTEX_M_OBJECT'\"\n"
"\n"
"[stack.fw]\n"
"repos = [\"littlefs\"]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:71
msgid "Real captured output (`haw build` then `haw test`, both exit 0):"
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:88
msgid ""
"`armv7e-m` is the Cortex-M4 ISA — a genuine bare-metal ARM object, produced "
"by `arm-none-eabi-gcc` inside Docker, orchestrated by `haw`, with a "
"native-machine `haw`."
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:93
msgid "Recipe 2 — QEMU emulated run (FreeRTOS on Cortex-M3) ✅ _executed_"
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:95
msgid ""
"The official FreeRTOS QEMU demo built with the FreeRTOS-Kernel, then "
"**booted on `qemu-system-arm -M mps2-an385 -cpu cortex-m3`**. The scheduler "
"runs the blinky demo (a task + a software timer feeding a queue) and prints "
"over the semihosted UART; `test =` greps for a live marker, so a genuinely "
"running RTOS exits 0 and a dead image exits 1."
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:100
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[repo.freertos]\n"
"url    = \"https://github.com/FreeRTOS/FreeRTOS.git\"\n"
"rev    = \"main\"\n"
"groups = [\"rtos\"]\n"
"build  = \"docker run --rm -v \\\"$PWD\\\":/w -w /w haw-arm-emu make -C "
"FreeRTOS/Demo/CORTEX_MPS2_QEMU_IAR_GCC/build/gcc\"\n"
"test   = \"docker run --rm -v \\\"$PWD\\\":/w -w /w haw-arm-emu sh -c "
"'timeout 8 qemu-system-arm -machine mps2-an385 -cpu cortex-m3 -kernel "
"FreeRTOS/Demo/CORTEX_MPS2_QEMU_IAR_GCC/build/gcc/output/RTOSDemo.out "
"-monitor none -nographic -serial stdio -semihosting-config "
"enable=on,target=native 2>&1 | head -40 | grep -q \\\"Message received from "
"task\\\" && echo QEMU_FREERTOS_RUN_CONFIRMED'\"\n"
"\n"
"[stack.rtos]\n"
"repos = [\"freertos\"]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:112
msgid "Real captured output:"
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:114
msgid ""
"```console\n"
"$ haw build        # relinks output/RTOSDemo.out\n"
"   text    data     bss     dec     hex  filename\n"
"  23902     232  121589  145723   2393b  ./output/RTOSDemo.out\n"
"build ran in 1/1 repos\n"
"\n"
"$ haw test         # FreeRTOS scheduler actually executing under QEMU\n"
"── freertos ──\n"
"Message received from task\n"
"Message received from task\n"
"... (37 total, plus 3 \"Message received from software timer\") ...\n"
"QEMU_FREERTOS_RUN_CONFIRMED\n"
"test ran in 1/1 repos\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:129
msgid ""
"Negative control verified: point the grep at a marker that never appears and "
"the QEMU step exits 1 — so `haw test` genuinely fails if the RTOS doesn't "
"boot, rather than always passing."
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:132
msgid ""
"**Submodules are fault-tolerant.** `haw sync --recurse-submodules` "
"initializes each submodule independently and **skips broken/unreachable ones "
"with a warning** instead of aborting — important for big upstream repos like "
"`FreeRTOS/FreeRTOS` that declare a large forest of heavy submodules "
"(wolfSSL, several AWS IoT SDKs, …). The kernel your target needs "
"(`FreeRTOS/Source`) is initialized; a submodule that 404s just prints `haw: "
"skipped submodule '<path>': …` and the sync still succeeds. "
"(`ext`/`fd`/`file` transports stay hard-disabled in submodule fetches — the "
"RCE guard is preserved.)"
msgstr ""

#: ./INTEGRATION.md:140
msgid ""
"Swap QEMU for **Renode** with one line — `test = \"renode --console -e "
"'include @sim.resc; start; sleep 5; quit'\"` then grep the UART log the same "
"way."
msgstr ""

