#: ./PLUGINS.md:410
msgid ""
"The plugin contract is **language-agnostic** — it is just JSON on `HAW_JSON` "
"/ stdin (`haw.plugin/1`) and JSON on stdout (`haw.plugin.report/1` for "
"lifecycle phases, `haw.plugin.view/1` for TUI render intent). Any language "
"that can read an env var and print JSON can be a haw plugin."
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:415
msgid ""
"The [`schemas/`](https://github.com/Nastwinns/hawser/tree/main/schemas) "
"directory holds the **official JSON Schemas** (draft 2020-12) — the source "
"of truth for every field name and shape. Validate your plugin's I/O against "
"them."
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:419
msgid ""
"Thin reference bindings mirror those schemas so you don't hand-roll the JSON:"
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:421
msgid ""
"**Python** — "
"[`bindings/python`](https://github.com/Nastwinns/hawser/tree/main/bindings/python) "
"(`haw_plugin`): `Context.from_env()`, `Report.emit()`, `view(title, lines)`. "
"No deps beyond stdlib."
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:423
msgid ""
"**Go** — "
"[`bindings/go`](https://github.com/Nastwinns/hawser/tree/main/bindings/go) "
"(`hawplugin`): `ReadContext()`, `Report.Emit()`, `View(title, lines)`. "
"Stdlib only."
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:425
msgid ""
"**POSIX shell** and **Rust** — the "
"[`examples/haw-hello`](https://github.com/Nastwinns/hawser/tree/main/examples/haw-hello) "
"and the \"Hello, plugin\" section above show zero-dependency implementations."
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:428
msgid ""
"For a curated list of existing plugins to install or learn from, see "
"[AWESOME-HAW-PLUGINS.md](https://github.com/Nastwinns/hawser/blob/main/AWESOME-HAW-PLUGINS.md)."
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:431
msgid "Conventions"
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:433
msgid ""
"**Name it `haw-<verb>`.** The verb is what users type: `haw-jira` → `haw "
"jira`. Keep it short and unclaimed by built-ins (`haw --help` lists those)."
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:435
msgid ""
"**Self-describing `--help`.** Users discover your plugin's flags through it; "
"haw does not document plugins for you."
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:437
msgid ""
"**Human on stdout, JSON on `--format json`.** Print a readable line by "
"default; emit a `haw.plugin/1` document (or your own versioned schema) under "
"`--format json` so other tools can pipe you."
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:440
msgid ""
"**Exit codes carry meaning.** `0` = success. Non-zero = failure, and haw "
"propagates it — CI gates and `&&` chains rely on it. Don't exit `0` on error."
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:442
msgid ""
"**Fail open.** Handle the workspace-less context (schema-only JSON) "
"gracefully. Don't assume `root`/`repos` exist. Never hang: your process "
"blocks haw until it exits."
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:444
msgid ""
"**Stay a separate process.** You get isolation for free — don't try to reach "
"into haw's internals; consume `--format json` and the `haw.plugin/1` context "
"instead."
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:447
msgid "Distributing your plugin"
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:449
msgid "Any executable named `haw-<name>` on `PATH` works. Two common paths:"
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:451
msgid ""
"**Publish a crate.** Name the binary `haw-<name>`; users get it with `cargo "
"install haw-<name>`, which drops it into `~/.cargo/bin` (usually on `PATH`)."
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:453
msgid ""
"**Ship a binary or script.** Drop `haw-<name>` into any `PATH` directory "
"(`/usr/local/bin`, `~/.local/bin`, `~/bin`). Shell scripts count — mark them "
"executable."
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:457
msgid "Verify with:"
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:464
msgid "Submitting your plugin"
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:466
msgid ""
"Built something useful? Share it. See "
"[CONTRIBUTING.md](https://github.com/Nastwinns/hawser/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md) "
"for the build/test checklist and PR etiquette, then open a PR that adds your "
"plugin to the community list — one line: name, one-sentence description, and "
"a link. We keep core small on purpose; the ecosystem lives in plugins."
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:471
msgid "Lifecycle phases"
msgstr ""

#: ./PLUGINS.md:473
msgid ""
"Plugins can subscribe to lifecycle phases in the manifest's `[plugins]` "
"table and are invoked out-of-process with `--haw-phase <name>` (e.g. an SBOM "
"plugin on `post-build`). The optional `haw-plugin` SDK crate gives Rust "
"authors the `Context`/`Report` ergonomics while still compiling to a "
"standalone `haw-<name>` binary."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:1
msgid "hawser — Compliance, Certification & Security Specification"
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:3
msgid ""
"Target market: safety- and security-critical programs (avionics, space, "
"defense, rail, automotive, industrial, medical). These buyers cannot adopt "
"an SCM tool unless it produces **certification evidence**, is itself "
"**qualifiable**, has an auditable **security posture**, and is "
"**data-protection clean**. This document specifies what hawser must provide, "
"per domain, and maps each requirement to a technical feature and a delivery "
"phase."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:9
msgid ""
"Terminology: \"the tool\" = the `haw` binary + `haw-core`. \"The applicant\" "
"= the customer's safety/security team who owns the certification argument. "
"hawser supplies **evidence and a qualification kit**; the applicant owns the "
"final determination in their plan (PSAC, safety plan, SEooC assumptions)."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:16
msgid "1. Where hawser sits in the lifecycle"
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:18
msgid ""
"hawser is a **Software Configuration Management (SCM) + composition** tool. "
"It decides _which revision of which repository enters a build_ and records "
"that decision immutably. It does **not** compile, generate, or verify "
"airborne/embedded code. That scoping is the single most important sentence "
"for qualification: it bounds the tool's failure modes to \"selects/records "
"the wrong source set\" — not \"emits wrong object code\"."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:24
msgid "Consequences of that scope:"
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:25
msgid ""
"The tool's output (`haw.lock` + materialized tree) is **verifiable "
"independently** by the downstream build + review, which lowers required "
"qualification rigor."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:27
msgid ""
"The evidence it produces (baseline, SBOM, provenance) is consumed by the "
"customer's SCM, safety, and security processes — hawser is an _evidence "
"producer_, not an authority."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:32
msgid "2. Tool qualification"
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:34
msgid ""
"hawser is **qualification-relevant** in every safety standard because a "
"config/composition tool can select the wrong source into a safety build. The "
"classification and rigor differ by standard; the _artifacts_ hawser must "
"supply are largely shared (§2.6)."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:38
msgid "2.1 DO-178C / DO-330 (airborne) & DO-278A (ground/ATM)"
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:39
msgid ""
"Tool qualification governed by **DO-330**. Criterion is set by whether the "
"tool can insert an error into the product and/or fail to detect one:"
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:41
msgid ""
"If the customer's process re-verifies the materialized tree/build "
"independently → **Criterion 3** → typically **TQL-5** (lowest rigor)."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:43
msgid ""
"If the lockfile/tree is trusted without independent re-verification → "
"**Criterion 1** → **TQL-4** (or higher at DAL A/B)."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:45
msgid ""
"hawser's recommendation to applicants: keep the downstream build+review as "
"the verifying activity so the tool stays Criterion 3 / TQL-5. Document this "
"in the PSAC."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:47
msgid ""
"Deliverables hawser supplies: **Tool Operational Requirements (TOR)**, "
"**Tool Qualification Plan (TQP)**, tool requirements + test cases + results "
"with traceability, **Tool Accomplishment Summary (TAS)** template, and a "
"**known-limitations / errata** list."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:51
msgid "2.2 ISO 26262-8:2018 §11 (automotive) + ASPICE"
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:52
msgid ""
"Determine **Tool Confidence Level** TCL1–3 from Tool Impact (TI) × Tool "
"error Detection (TD). hawser is TI2 (a malfunction can violate a safety "
"requirement) with achievable TD1/TD2 if the customer verifies the build → "
"typically **TCL1–TCL2**."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:55
msgid ""
"Qualification methods hawser supports: **1a** increased confidence from use "
"(usage metrics, field-history template), **1b** evaluation of the tool "
"development process (our SDLC evidence, §7), **1c** validation of the tool "
"(our test suite + results)."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:58
msgid ""
"ASPICE mapping: **SUP.8 Configuration Management** and **SUP.10 Change "
"Request Management** (see §3). Provide the mapping table as a sales/audit "
"artifact."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:61
msgid "2.3 IEC 61508-3 (industrial functional safety)"
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:62
msgid ""
"Offline support tool classification **T2/T3**. hawser contributes to what is "
"built → treat as **T3** unless the customer's build independently re-derives "
"the source set."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:64
msgid ""
"Supply: tool validation evidence, version + configuration record, "
"known-defects list."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:66
msgid "2.4 EN 50128 / EN 50716 (rail)"
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:67
msgid ""
"Tool class **T2/T3** (§6.7). Supply a **Tool Qualification Report** and "
"evidence the tool is used within its validated operating envelope."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:70
msgid "2.5 Space (ECSS-E-ST-40 / ECSS-Q-ST-80) & medical (IEC 62304)"
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:71
msgid ""
"Space: tool used within an SCM plan; supply configuration + validation "
"records."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:72
msgid ""
"Medical IEC 62304 §8 SOUP/configuration management: supply SBOM + baseline "
"evidence."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:74
msgid ""
"2.6 The shared qualification artifact set (produced once, mapped per "
"standard)"
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:75
msgid ""
"**Tool Operational Requirements** — what `haw` shall do, in verifiable "
"statements."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:76
msgid ""
"**Requirements → test traceability matrix** (every requirement has a test)."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:77
msgid ""
"**Test suite + machine-readable results** per released LTS, per supported OS."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:78
msgid ""
"**Safety/Operation Manual** — intended use, operating envelope, constraints, "
"and the **error-avoidance measures the user must apply** (e.g. \"commit the "
"lockfile\", \"verify the build re-derives the tree\")."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:81
msgid "**Known limitations & errata**, versioned."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:82
msgid ""
"**Configuration record** — exact tool version, dependency versions, build "
"provenance."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:83
msgid ""
"**Per-standard mapping tables** (DO-330 / ISO 26262-8 / IEC 61508 / EN 50128 "
"/ ASPICE)."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:85
msgid ""
"Determinism is a hard requirement for all of the above: same inputs ⇒ "
"byte-identical `haw.lock` and tree selection, on every OS. No wall-clock, no "
"map iteration order, no network nondeterminism in resolution. See §8."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:91
msgid "3. Reproducibility & SCM evidence"
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:93
msgid ""
"The commercial and certification wedge. hawser turns \"trust our process\" "
"into \"here is the signed, reproducible baseline\"."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:96
msgid ""
"**`haw.lock` = the configuration baseline.** Every repo pinned to an exact "
"object id. Committed, diff-reviewable, machine-verifiable."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:98
msgid ""
"**Deterministic resolution.** Documented, versioned resolution algorithm "
"(see `resolver/mod.rs`); overlay precedence is total and stable."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:100
msgid ""
"**Drift detection.** `haw status` / `haw verify` proves the on-disk tree "
"matches the baseline — this _is_ a configuration verification activity for "
"the customer's SCM plan."
msgstr ""

#: ./COMPLIANCE.md:102
msgid ""
"**Evidence bundle.** `haw evidence` emits: baseline (lock) + SBOM + "
"provenance attestation + tool configuration record, as one signed archive "
"for the cert data package."
msgstr ""

